I think the article is just as relevant for T1's too. In my case, my
current doc looked at my A1C's (which were truly excellent) and all
the risk factors (especially a deep deep family history) for heart
disease, and decided that my diabetes or complications of it wouldn't
kill me, it would be heart disease. Yes, diabetes is certainly one of
the risk factors for heart disease

I do disagree with a couple of sentences in the NYT article most
notably &quot;[emphasizing] blood sugar control is difficult and expensive
and has not been proven to save lives&quot;, which I partly agree with
(difficult and expensive) and disagree with (I was in a coma 25 years
ago, my first week with diabetes, nobody can tell me that controlling
my bg didn't save my life!)

But the emphasis on having to look at other aspects of health beyond
just bg, especially after bg's have been brought into control, is
something that many of my diabetes-concentrating endos had not done a
good job of for several decades. I feel so so so much better now that
my other aspects of health are being taken care of too (and there is
so much more work to do too!)

Tim.
