I mostly agree. I thought the issue of needing to address heart disease
risks more generally than by controlling blood sugar was important, though.

I also think that the British study that showed controlling bg didn't lower
heart disease risks has flaws. I've seen more detailed analyses that seem to
say that measuring control by A1c isn't good enough and that you have to
also look at variability. When the data were re-analyzed with variability
measured within A1c catagories, it was obvious that control was actually
very effective.

And I wonder about the talk about weight loss not being very efffective.
With the recent discoveries about metabolic signaling within visceral fat,
it may be that people don't lose enough weight to do the job. I don't think
we really know.

Certainly there is more to treating diabetes than controlling bg.
Controlling insulin also comes to mind...
