I'd say the evidence on the importance of LDL lowering is a bit murky. We
know that lowering LDL with a statin reduces mortality and cardiac morbidity
in diabetics. But we can't yet really tease out whether the benefit is from
the lowered LDL or the statin in some other way.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;But targets aren't the only consideration: it's *how* you get your bg
&gt;and lipids to goals that's important.  Eating and living in a way that
&gt;achieves goals is far more protective because you're not fighting
&gt;damaging processes with chemical interventions.
">

For sure people with DM and heart disease didn't get them because they
weren't taking the right drugs. They got them from genetics and lifestyle.
Once they have them, they may need drugs to help them. Or, they may not if
lifestyle changes will do the job for them.

It would be easier to see this with clarity if we could run studies where we
could control LDL down to 60 or so without a drug or with different
unrelated drugs so we could sort out the LDL effect from the other possible
confounding effects of a statin.

The NYT article was definitely negative re what the patient could do apart
from taking a number of drugs.
