I read the other responses to date.

This is the part that sets the scene:

&quot;Mr. Smith, a 43-year-old pastor in Fairmont, Minn., tried
hard. When dieting did not work, he began counting
carbohydrates, taking pills to lower his blood sugar and
pricking his finger several times a day to measure his sugar
levels. They remained high, so he agreed to add insulin to
his already complicated regimen. Blood sugar was always on
his mind.

But in focusing entirely on blood sugar, Mr. Smith ended up
neglecting the most important treatment for saving lives —
lowering the cholesterol level. That protects against heart
disease, which eventually kills nearly everyone with
diabetes.

He also was missing a second treatment that protects
diabetes patients from heart attacks — controlling blood
pressure. Mr. Smith assumed everything would be taken care
of if he could just lower his blood sugar level.&quot;

For Mr Smith all that may have been true. But the article
extends those false presumptions by implication to all type
2's.

The specific critical mistake is here: &quot;When dieting did not
work, he began counting carbohydrates, taking pills to lower
his blood sugar and pricking his finger several times a day
to measure his sugar levels.&quot;

First, dieting needs definition - what diet, what was it's
purpose (weight loss, BG management, lipids management,
other?). Next - how did he count carbs, using what method
and to what purpose? Next - what system was he following for
BG testing?

If, for example the diet he followed was that advocated by
the majority of dieticians reported here by newbies on
arrival, and by my own dietician, it would be low-fat, high
carb.

If he counted carbs using the exchange system or that
advocated by the majority of dieticians reported here, and
my own dietician, it would be 30-45 grams at every meal and
15 gms for snacks, with 5 veges and 2 fruits every day.
Regardless of the post-meal BG results.

If he pricked his finger several times a day in accordance
with the advice reported by most newbies here, and my own
doctor, it would be fasting, pre-dinner and maybe two hours
after each meal without using any of those tests to review
his menu. At most he reported the results to his doc, who
upped his meds and then suggested insulin.

Why am I not surprised that his diet, carb counting, testing
and the meds he was taking not only did not improve his BG's
but led to high cholesterol and high blood pressure? Because
we see Mr Smith arrive here daily. I also meet him on Yahoo
Groups and the ADA forum. We see the results of that system.

Nearly every person who appears here as a newby and then
bothers to drop in again months later with a follow-up not
only reports improvements in BG's and A1c but also in
weight, cholesterol, blood pressure and other health
aspects.

Those who succeeded started by focusing on BG's using test,
test, test and exercise. Along the way they reviewed their
menu constantly to not only improve BG's but to add variety
and good nutrition without raising BG's. That awareness of
what was going on in their bodies led to improvements in all
areas, not just one.

And that takes us back to that critical mistake - it's not
that diet did not work, it's that the correct way of eating
is the critical platform that all the other parts of type 2
diabetes and heart health management are founded on. If the
diet is actively working against the meds, exercise and
insulin - then they will fail. As they did for Mr Smith; and
as they will in his future if he keeps adding meds and
insulin to a poor foundation.

Just my opinion.

Cheers, Alan, T2, Australia.
