In a 5 year study of people with known vascular disease and/or diabetes,
mortality was reduced 17% in men and 19% in women on statins due to
fewer heart disease deaths.  Overall mortality reduction was 13% on
statins, which indicates that some number of people in the control group
died of other causes at a higher rate (but that was not statistically
significant... I expect we'd need a larger sample size to examine that
issue).

I don't see any methodological problems with the study - it looks
persuasive to me.  There may well be risks associated with statins that
this study didn't pick up because it wasn't large enough or long-term
enough, but a 13% reduction in mortality in 5 years is a pretty
persuasive argument to me.  Death is pretty much the mother of all
adverse effects.

My personal conclusion is to renew my prescription for pravastatin as
I'm both a heart patient and a diabetic.

