It's bad journalism - but not for that reason. I'm not
refuting the link between diabetes and heart disease in any
way. There is an obvious link and all of us here are more
than aware of it. If I remember correctly to be diagnosed as
a type 2 diabetic is equivalent to the same risk as having
had your first heart attack. I disagree with several things
in that article - but that is not one of them. My prime
disagreement is on their focus and their clear implication
that BG's are less important than BP or Lipids.

To be specific, from what I've read, there is a far closer
and more provable link between death and HbA1c for type 2
than there is for a link between death and LDL or death and
hypertension. All three are high risk factors - but to
ignore BG's as the primary one for diabetics is ridiculous
and dangerous. Further, my own experience and that of many
other type 2's I have corresponded with and met personally
is that when diet and exercise are used as the primary means
of BG management and meds are used as the secondary or
complementary then lipids and hypertension are usually
improved at the same time.

Jim Chinnis mentioned this excerpt from a paper on statins
and LDL: &quot;This shows a 23% reduction in all-cause mortality
just from a stronger statin dose corresponding to an average
change in LDL from 87 mg/dl to 64. Impressive, right? I must
admit that's the strongest case I've heard in favour of
statins and LDL reduction for a while, although I haven't
read the detail. It's also the only one I've seen that comes
out that strongly.

However, when I compare it to this, I doubt I'll give up
recommending test, test, test:

&quot;HbA1c was continuously related to subsequent all cause,
cardiovascular, and ischaemic heart disease mortality
through the whole population distribution, with lowest rates
in those with HbA1c concentrations below 5%. An increase of
1% in HbA1c was associated with a 28% (P&lt;0.002) increase in
risk of death independent of age, blood pressure, serum
cholesterol, body mass index, and cigarette smoking habit;&quot;

I think any diabetic who ignores BG's and concentrates only
on lipids and BP is mad. And that is the clear signal in
that article; not just in the text - look at the nice photo
and comment on the guy who tests rarely having a good time
in his orchard.

I have no figures on hypertension drugs and death - but I do
test at home and I do ensure my BP is OK.

BG's, lipids, BP; they are all only part of the whole, but
for us as type 2's if we don't gain reasonable control of
the BG's the others won't matter. The other message in that
article is that diet doesn't work, meds are essential and
progression is inevitable. Read it again in full.

