&gt; had your first heart attack. I disagree with several things
&gt; in that article - but that is not one of them. My prime
&gt; disagreement is on their focus and their clear implication
&gt; that BG's are less important than BP or Lipids.
">

Well, I honestly don't know what's more or less important. I did not
agree with every quote in the article and I've already clearly stated
here that I think the quote that controlling bg being unproven to save
lives is wrong for me (I'm not a Type 2 but will generalize at least
some of my beliefs beyond my little lesser-numbered type!)

But if I look at the risk factor lists associated with cardiovascular
disease, diabetes is usually just one of seven or one of thirteen.
That doesn't mean that all the risk factors are equally weighted -
it's pretty obvious they aren't all equal.

What I read in the NY Times article was that getting good bg control
doesn't eliminate the diabetes risk factor, and it doesn't do much to
help any of the other twelve risk factors at all. And that's the story
I took away from it, and I think it's a good story.

When it comes to going over news articles with a fine-toothed comb, I
cannot fault the reporter for quoting a knowledgable source as to what
he said. Sometimes I think the context is lost, and that's
unfortunate, but it's important not to get all bent out of shape just
because the context was lost around a single quote. I've been quoted
out of context several times in national publications (most recently
the Washington Post) and don't hold it against the reporter.

Tim.
